1. Load Required Library

We load the ggplot2 library for visualization.

library(ggplot2)

2. Load the Dataset

The dataset contains global temperature records over time.

global_temp <- read.csv("GlobalTemperatures.csv")

3. Convert Date Column

We convert the date column to a proper Date type for time series analysis.

global_temp$dt <- as.Date(global_temp$dt)

4. Remove Missing Values

To ensure data quality, we remove rows containing missing values.

cleaned_data <- na.omit(global_temp)

5. Remove Extreme Outliers

We use the IQR method to filter extreme outliers in LandAverageTemperature.

Q1 <- quantile(cleaned_data$LandAverageTemperature, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
Q3 <- quantile(cleaned_data$LandAverageTemperature, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
IQR <- Q3 - Q1
lower_bound <- Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound <- Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

filtered_data <- cleaned_data[
  cleaned_data$LandAverageTemperature >= lower_bound & cleaned_data$LandAverageTemperature <= upper_bound, ]

6. Line Chart: Global Temperature Change Over Time

We create a line plot to visualize how global temperatures have changed over time.

line_plot <- ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = dt, y = LandAverageTemperature)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Global Temperature Change Over Time", x = "Year", y = "Average Temperature (C)") +
  theme_minimal()

# Save line chart
ggsave("global_temp_trend.png", plot = line_plot, width = 8, height = 6)

7. Scatter Plot: Avg Temperature vs.Max Temperature

We create a scatter plot to analyze the relationship between LandAverageTemperature and LandMaxTemperature.

scatter_plot <- ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = LandAverageTemperature, y = LandMaxTemperature)) +
  geom_point(color = "red", alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(title = "Avg Temperature vs. Max Temperature", 
       x = "Land Average Temperature (C)", 
       y = "Land Max Temperature (C)") +
  theme_minimal()

# Save scatter plot
ggsave("avg_vs_max_temp.png", plot = scatter_plot, width = 8, height = 6)

8. Display Plots

Finally, we display both plots in the output.

print(line_plot)

print(scatter_plot)
